---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import profileImage from '../assets/profile.webp';

const essays = [
	{
		title: "Strategic Silence and Negotiation Agents: Teach Your AI to Shut Up",
		blurb: "Where agentic engineering meets negotiation, and why knowing when to stay quiet is a feature.",
		url: "https://negotiations.substack.com",
	},
	{
		title: "Negotiating in the Age of LLMs",
		blurb: "A practical framework for winning when the counterparty runs on probability.",
		url: "https://negotiations.substack.com",
	},
	{
		title: "How to Negotiate with Trump: 3 Game-Theory Strategies",
		blurb: "Credible commitments, exit options, and strategic signaling in high-stakes deals.",
		url: "https://negotiations.substack.com/p/how-to-negotiate-with-trump-game-theory",
	},
	{
		title: "Solving Complexity in Global Diplomacy: The Iran Nuclear Negotiations",
		blurb: "How embracing complexity produces durable diplomatic outcomes.",
		url: "https://negotiations.substack.com/p/solving-complexity-in-global-diplomacy",
	},
];

const tools = [
	{
		name: "P2Predict",
		blurb: "Machine-learning command-line tool for advanced procurement price prediction.",
		url: "https://github.com/ahmed-khalil-hafsi/P2Predict",
	},
	{
		name: "P2CLPFD",
		blurb: "A dynamic-programming framework for supplier allocation problems (GPLv3).",
		url: "https://github.com/ahmed-khalil-hafsi/P2CLPFD",
	},
];
---

<Layout
	description="Ahmed K. Hafsi on negotiation and game theory: how power, incentives, and leverage shape outcomes in business, technology, and geopolitics."
>
	<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
		<!-- Intro -->
		<section class="pt-12 md:pt-16">
			<div class="flex items-center gap-5 mb-8">
				<Image
					src={profileImage}
					alt="Ahmed K. Hafsi"
					class="w-24 h-24 md:w-28 md:h-28 object-cover rounded-full border border-rule flex-shrink-0"
					width={256}
					height={256}
					quality={88}
					loading="eager"
				/>
				<div>
					<h1 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-ink tracking-tight">Ahmed K. Hafsi</h1>
					<p class="text-muted mt-1 text-base md:text-lg">Negotiation · Game Theory · Strategy · APAC (Singapore)</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<p class="text-xl md:text-2xl leading-snug text-ink font-display">
				I work on negotiation and applied game theory: how power, incentives, and leverage shape outcomes at the negotiating table, in markets, and in geopolitics.
			</p>

			<div class="mt-6 space-y-4 text-ink/90">
				<p>
					I'm Senior Manager, Negotiation Excellence at <strong>Infineon</strong>, where I build and run a negotiation operating model that delivers verifiable value through commercial terms: pricing, indexation, and governance. My focus is industrials across the Asia-Pacific, from automotive and semiconductors to consumer tech and chemicals. Singapore is my launch pad, and I work all over the region, from Japan to Indonesia.
				</p>
				<p>
					Before Infineon I architected and led <strong>Dyson's</strong> global Negotiation Excellence capability, and earlier I advised industrial clients on negotiation and game theory at <strong>TWS Partners</strong> in Munich and London. I trained as an engineer at the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology, and I have worked across three continents in four languages.
				</p>
				<p>
					My newsletter, <a href="https://negotiations.substack.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Games &amp; Negotiations</a>, is where I think out loud about all of this.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="my-12 border-rule" />

		<!-- How I think about negotiation -->
		<section>
			<h2 class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold text-ink mb-5">How I think about negotiation</h2>
			<div class="space-y-4 text-ink/90">
				<p>
					Negotiation is structural analysis. Every negotiation sits inside a system of interests, constraints, and expectations, and the outcome is largely set before anyone speaks: by who holds leverage, what each side genuinely needs, and how their incentives line up under pressure and incomplete information.
				</p>
				<p>
					Get that structure right and the tactics follow. So my work starts upstream of the table. I map the ecosystem, locate the real leverage, and design the <em>architecture</em> of the agreement: how pricing, indexation, and terms allocate value and risk across the whole life of the relationship.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="mt-6 border-l-2 border-accent pl-5 space-y-2 text-ink/90">
				<p><strong>Structure first.</strong> Diagnose the system before choosing words.</p>
				<p><strong>Leverage is built.</strong> Alternatives, information, and timing can be engineered.</p>
				<p><strong>Design for the whole horizon.</strong> The terms govern for years; price is day one.</p>
				<p><strong>Read the incentives.</strong> People are predictable once you see what they optimize for.</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="my-12 border-rule" />

		<!-- Game theory -->
		<section>
			<h2 class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold text-ink mb-5">Game theory, in practice</h2>
			<div class="space-y-4 text-ink/90">
				<p>
					Game theory is a practical lens. It takes a messy, emotional situation and asks the disciplined questions. Who are the real players, including the ones not in the room? What are their payoffs? Which moves are credible? Where can a <strong>credible commitment</strong>, a visible <strong>exit option</strong>, or careful <strong>signaling</strong> shift the equilibrium in your favor?
				</p>
				<p>
					Add behavioral science, how people actually decide under risk, framing, and time pressure, and negotiation becomes legible and closer to engineering. You shape the game itself.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="my-12 border-rule" />

		<!-- What I'm exploring -->
		<section>
			<h2 class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold text-ink mb-5">What I'm exploring now</h2>
			<div class="space-y-4 text-ink/90">
				<p>
					Technology is rewriting the table. I am especially interested in AI and large language models, both as tools that change how we prepare and as <em>negotiating actors</em> in their own right. What does it mean to bargain against a counterparty that runs on probability? When should an autonomous agent stay silent? I write about these questions as they develop, alongside the enduring ones: supplier networks, leverage in concentrated markets, and the strategic logic behind geopolitical power shifts.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="my-12 border-rule" />

		<!-- Writing -->
		<section>
			<div class="flex items-baseline justify-between mb-5 gap-4">
				<h2 class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold text-ink">Selected writing</h2>
				<a href="/newsletter" class="text-accent text-sm whitespace-nowrap">All essays →</a>
			</div>
			<ul class="space-y-5">
				{essays.map((e) => (
					<li>
						<a href={e.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="font-display text-lg text-ink hover:text-accent transition-colors">
							{e.title}
						</a>
						<p class="text-muted mt-1">{e.blurb}</p>
					</li>
				))}
			</ul>
		</section>

		<hr class="my-12 border-rule" />

		<!-- Tools -->
		<section>
			<h2 class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold text-ink mb-3">Open-source tools</h2>
			<p class="text-muted mb-5">Bringing game-theoretic thinking and data science to procurement and supply-chain decisions.</p>
			<ul class="space-y-5">
				{tools.map((t) => (
					<li>
						<a href={t.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="font-display text-lg text-ink hover:text-accent transition-colors">
							{t.name}
						</a>
						<p class="text-muted mt-1">{t.blurb}</p>
					</li>
				))}
			</ul>
		</section>

		<hr class="my-12 border-rule" />

		<!-- Closer -->
		<section class="pb-4">
			<p class="text-ink/90">
				More about my background is on the <a href="/about">about page</a>, and you can reach me via the <a href="/contact">contact page</a> or on
				<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ahmedkhalilhafsi/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">LinkedIn</a>.
			</p>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>
